  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="9">arXiv</subfield>
    <subfield code="a">We perform a systematic study of the generic Gatto-Sartori-Tonin relation, $\tan^2\theta_{ij}= m_i/m_j$; finding by this, the necessary conditions to be met in order to obtain it, without any approximations, in fermion mixing. We begin by considering two Dirac fermion families. From a mathematical viewpoint, it is found that a sufficient and necessary condition is to have a normal matrix with $m_{11}=0$. Thereafter, this condition is translated into a physical statement: the Yukawa couplings between the different fermion families should be added as various sets obeying, each of them, distinct symmetrical properties under permutations of the corresponding massless fields. In general, it is shown that the symmetrical properties of the introduced set of Yukawa couplings follows, for $n$ fermion families, a unique sequential ordering $S_{nL}\otimes S_{nR} \rightarrow S_{(n-1)L}\otimes S_{(n-1)R} \rightarrow \cdots \rightarrow S_{2L}\otimes S_{2R} \rightarrow S_{2A}$. The particular case of three fermion families not only gives the desired Gatto-Sartori-Tonin relation but also explains why fermion mixing is decomposed into various two families mixing as recently we observed in the study of the hierarchical properties of the mass matrices.</subfield>
  </datafield>
